36#define CODE_EVENTS_TYPE_LIST(V) \
37 V(kCodeCreation, CodeCreateEventRecord) \
38 V(kCodeMove, CodeMoveEventRecord) \
39 V(kCodeDisableOpt, CodeDisableOptEventRecord) \
40 V(kCodeDeopt, CodeDeoptEventRecord) \
41 V(kReportBuiltin, ReportBuiltinEventRecord) \
42 V(kCodeDelete, CodeDeleteEventRecord)

44#define VM_EVENTS_TYPE_LIST(V) \
45 CODE_EVENTS_TYPE_LIST(V) \
46 V(kNativeContextMove, NativeContextMoveEventRecord)

48class CodeEventRecord {
49 public:
50#define DECLARE_TYPE(type, ignore) type,
51 enum class Type { kNoEvent = 0, VM_EVENTS_TYPE_LIST(DECLARE_TYPE) };
52#undef DECLARE_TYPE
53
54 Type type;
55 mutable unsigned order;
56};

137// A record type for sending code events (e.g. create, move, delete) to the
138// profiling thread.
139class CodeEventsContainer {
140 public:
141 explicit CodeEventsContainer(
142 CodeEventRecord::Type type = CodeEventRecord::Type::kNoEvent) {
143 generic.type = type;
144 }
145 union {
146 CodeEventRecord generic;
147#define DECLARE_CLASS(ignore, type) type type##_;
148 VM_EVENTS_TYPE_LIST(DECLARE_CLASS)
149#undef DECLARE_CLASS
150 };
151};

236 // Tick sample events are filled directly in the buffer of the circular
237 // queue (because the structure is of fixed width, but usually not all
238 // stack frame entries are filled.) This method returns a pointer to the
239 // next record of the buffer.
240 // These methods are not thread-safe and should only ever be called by one
241 // producer (from CpuSampler::SampleStack()). For testing, use AddSample.
242 inline TickSample* StartTickSample();
243 inline void FinishTickSample();

245 sampler::Sampler* sampler() { return sampler_.get(); }
246 base::TimeDelta period() const { return period_; }

248 private:
249 SampleProcessingResult ProcessOneSample() override;
250 void SymbolizeAndAddToProfiles(const TickSampleEventRecord* record);
251
252 static const size_t kTickSampleBufferSize = 512 * KB;
253 static const size_t kTickSampleQueueLength =
254 kTickSampleBufferSize / sizeof(TickSampleEventRecord);
255 SamplingCircularQueue<TickSampleEventRecord,
256 kTickSampleQueueLength> ticks_buffer_;
257 std::unique_ptr<sampler::Sampler> sampler_;
258 base::TimeDelta period_; // Samples & code events processing period.
259 const bool use_precise_sampling_; // Whether or not busy-waiting is used for
260 // low sampling intervals on Windows.
261#if V8_OS_WIN
262 base::PreciseSleepTimer precise_sleep_timer_;
263#endif // V8_OS_WIN
264};

281

284
285 void CodeEventHandlerInternal(const CodeEventsContainer& evt_rec);
286
287 void CreateEntriesForRuntimeCallStats();
288 void LogBuiltins();
289
290 ProfilerEventsProcessor* processor() { return processor_; }
291
292 // Redirects code events to be enqueued on the given events processor.

294 processor_ = processor;

296

301 CodeEntryStorage& code_entries_;
302 InstructionStreamMap code_map_;
303 WeakCodeRegistry weak_code_registry_;
304 ProfilerEventsProcessor* processor_;

307// The CpuProfiler is a sampling CPU profiler for JS frames. It corresponds to
308// v8::CpuProfiler at the API level. It spawns an additional thread which is
309// responsible for triggering samples and then symbolizing the samples with
310// function names. To symbolize on a background thread, the profiler copies
311// metadata about generated code off-heap.
312//
313// Sampling is done using posix signals (except on Windows). The profiling
314// thread sends a signal to the main thread, based on a timer. The signal
315// handler can interrupt the main thread between any abitrary instructions.
316// This means we are very careful about reading stack values during the signal
317// handler as we could be in the middle of an operation that is modifying the
318// stack.
319//
320// The story on Windows is similar except we use thread suspend and resume.
321//
322// Samples are passed to the profiling thread via a circular buffer. The
323// profiling thread symbolizes the samples by looking up the code pointers
324// against its own list of code objects. The profiling thread also listens for
325// code creation/move/deletion events (from the GC), to maintain its list of
326// code objects accurately.
327class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE CpuProfiler {
328 public:
329 explicit CpuProfiler(Isolate* isolate, CpuProfilingNamingMode = kDebugNaming,
330 CpuProfilingLoggingMode = kLazyLogging);
331
332 CpuProfiler(Isolate* isolate, CpuProfilingNamingMode naming_mode,
333 CpuProfilingLoggingMode logging_mode,
334 CpuProfilesCollection* profiles, Symbolizer* test_symbolizer,
335 ProfilerEventsProcessor* test_processor,
336 ProfilerCodeObserver* test_code_observer);
337
338 ~CpuProfiler();
339 CpuProfiler(const CpuProfiler&) = delete;
340 CpuProfiler& operator=(const CpuProfiler&) = delete;
341
342 static void CollectSample(Isolate* isolate);
343 static size_t GetAllProfilersMemorySize(Isolate* isolate);
344
345 using ProfilingMode = v8::CpuProfilingMode;
346 using CpuProfilingResult = v8::CpuProfilingResult;
347 using NamingMode = v8::CpuProfilingNamingMode;
348 using LoggingMode = v8::CpuProfilingLoggingMode;
349 using StartProfilingStatus = CpuProfilingStatus;
350
351 base::TimeDelta sampling_interval() const { return base_sampling_interval_; }
352 void set_sampling_interval(base::TimeDelta value);
353 void set_use_precise_sampling(bool);
354 void CollectSample();
355 size_t GetEstimatedMemoryUsage() const;
356 CpuProfilingResult StartProfiling(
357 CpuProfilingOptions options = {},
358 std::unique_ptr<DiscardedSamplesDelegate> delegate = nullptr);
359 CpuProfilingResult StartProfiling(
360 const char* title, CpuProfilingOptions options = {},
361 std::unique_ptr<DiscardedSamplesDelegate> delegate = nullptr);
362 CpuProfilingResult StartProfiling(
363 Tagged<String> title, CpuProfilingOptions options = {},
364 std::unique_ptr<DiscardedSamplesDelegate> delegate = nullptr);
365
366 CpuProfile* StopProfiling(const char* title);
367 CpuProfile* StopProfiling(Tagged<String> title);
368 CpuProfile* StopProfiling(ProfilerId id);
369
370 int GetProfilesCount();
371 CpuProfile* GetProfile(int index);
372 void DeleteAllProfiles();

374
375 bool is_profiling() const { return is_profiling_; }
376
377 Symbolizer* symbolizer() const { return symbolizer_.get(); }
378 ProfilerEventsProcessor* processor() const { return processor_.get(); }
379 Isolate* isolate() const { return isolate_; }
380 CodeEntryStorage* code_entries() { return &code_entries_; }
381
382 ProfilerListener* profiler_listener_for_test() const {
383 return profiler_listener_.get();
384 }
385 InstructionStreamMap* code_map_for_test() {
386 return code_observer_->instruction_stream_map();
387 }
388
389 private:
390 void StartProcessorIfNotStarted();
391 void StopProcessor();
392 void ResetProfiles();

394 void EnableLogging();
395 void DisableLogging();
396
397 // Computes a sampling interval sufficient to accomodate attached profiles.
398 base::TimeDelta ComputeSamplingInterval();
399 // Dynamically updates the sampler to use a sampling interval sufficient for
400 // child profiles.
401 void AdjustSamplingInterval();
402
403 Isolate* const isolate_;
404 const NamingMode naming_mode_;
405 const LoggingMode logging_mode_;
406 bool use_precise_sampling_ = true;
407 // Sampling interval to which per-profile sampling intervals will be clamped
408 // to a multiple of, or used as the default if unspecified.
409 base::TimeDelta base_sampling_interval_;
410
411 // Storage for CodeEntry objects allocated by the profiler. May live for
412 // multiple profiling sessions, independent of heap listener state.
413 CodeEntryStorage code_entries_;
414
415 std::unique_ptr<ProfilerCodeObserver> code_observer_;
416 std::unique_ptr<CpuProfilesCollection> profiles_;

418 std::unique_ptr<ProfilerEventsProcessor> processor_;
419 std::unique_ptr<ProfilerListener> profiler_listener_;
420 std::unique_ptr<ProfilingScope> profiling_scope_;
421 bool is_profiling_;
422};
